      "excerpt": "The problem was that real user questions are rarely as tidy as the documents themselves. If someone asks using the exact words that already appear in a post, lexical search works well. But real questions do not always l…",
      "content": "But Static Search Started to Hit Its Limits Very Quickly\nThe problem was that real user questions are rarely as tidy as the documents themselves. If someone asks using the exact words that already appear in a post, lexical search works well. But real questions do not always look like that. The moment someone asks something like \"what is his name\" in English, or \"what is the shared design philosophy across this blog?\", plain string based search starts to run out of room. I ran into two main limitations. The first was phrasing. Even when the meaning was the same, slightly different wording often failed to line up with the exact words in the content. The second was scope. Some questions could not be answered from a single post. You had to look across the About page, project descriptions, and multiple blog posts together. Static search is good at finding \"documents with similar strings.\" It is not naturally good at assembling context from several documents and synthesizing them. There was one more thing on top of that: the identity of the chatbot itself. A question like \"what relationship do you have with this person?\" felt awkward to answer through public documents alone. It made mor…",
