      "excerpt": "My reasons for moving toward embedding based RAG were fairly straightforward. The biggest one was that I wanted to be less dependent on exact string matches. I wanted the system to find the right documents even when the…",
      "content": "That Was Why I Wanted to Try Embedding-Based RAG\nMy reasons for moving toward embedding based RAG were fairly straightforward. The biggest one was that I wanted to be less dependent on exact string matches. I wanted the system to find the right documents even when the same meaning was phrased differently. I also wanted it to gather evidence across multiple documents, not just from one article. On top of that, I wanted to index not only blog posts, but also about, projects, and even internal assistant documents. That felt much closer to a real site level chatbot than a glorified article search. There was still an obvious objection at this point. \"Wouldn't it be more natural to just let the LLM read the documents directly?\" That question is still valid. In fact, for prompts like \"hello\", \"who are you?\", or \"what is the latest post?\", a raw LLM can sometimes sound more natural. But that approach gets more expensive as the corpus grows, because you keep pushing long context into the model. It also gives you less control over what the answer is grounded in. Once I cared about things like \"do not speak as if you are the author,\" \"only use public information,\" and \"show which post suppor…",
