      "excerpt": "For a while, I experimented with hosting the embedding API myself through an external platform. The first platform I tried was Lightning AI. Using LitServe to expose a single embedding endpoint for both document embeddi…",
      "content": "Why I Tried Lightning AI, and Why I Stopped There\nFor a while, I experimented with hosting the embedding API myself through an external platform. The first platform I tried was Lightning AI. Using LitServe to expose a single embedding endpoint for both document embeddings and query embeddings looked pretty compelling. And during testing, it worked. I was able to send both documents and queries through the same endpoint and return OpenAI compatible embedding responses without too much trouble. The problem was the operating model. Studio was convenient for experiments because it gave me a free time window every time I spun it up. That made it useful for short tests like \"does the document embedding path work\" or \"does the query embedding path work.\" But it still felt like an environment for experimentation, not something I wanted to lean on for this specific production role. Deployment, on the other hand, was closer to production. But what I wanted was a light embedding only endpoint. Managing a continuously running deployment for that purpose felt heavier than I wanted, both in cost and in operational shape. An embedding server is only one piece of retrieval; it is not a user facin…",
