      "excerpt": "Actually building it changed the way I thought about the problem. At first, I vaguely assumed that adding embeddings would automatically make the chatbot smarter. I do not think that anymore. Embeddings are useful. They…",
      "content": "In the End, I Had to Separate Question Types\nActually building it changed the way I thought about the problem. At first, I vaguely assumed that adding embeddings would automatically make the chatbot smarter. I do not think that anymore. Embeddings are useful. They help reduce phrasing mismatch and gather evidence across multiple documents. But embeddings alone do not make a product. What turned out to matter even more was splitting question types correctly. Questions like \"hello\", \"how can I contact you?\", \"what is the latest post?\", and \"what is the oldest post?\" are closer to product logic than to retrieval. Questions like \"who are you?\", \"what kind of developer is this person?\", \"what is the main tech stack?\", and \"what design philosophy appears across this blog?\" depend much more on evidence retrieval. That is why the current structure now looks less like “send everything to retrieval” and more like “organize the question once before deciding what to do next.” Planner guided blog chatbot architecture The Question Planner in the middle is not there to force every prompt into one rigid category. It rewrites the question into something clearer, then decides whether the request ca…",
