      "excerpt": "When building side projects, file uploads usually get pushed to the end. You start with authentication, deployment, payments, and the core product flow, and only later think, \"I should probably support image uploads too…",
      "content": "How Leemage Grew from a Cost Problem into a File Management Platform\nWhen building side projects, file uploads usually get pushed to the end. You start with authentication, deployment, payments, and the core product flow, and only later think, \"I should probably support image uploads too.\" I used to treat uploads as a minor feature as well. But after repeating the same pattern across multiple projects, my perspective changed. The moment image uploads entered the picture, cost became a very practical issue. The feature itself looks simple, but depending on the service you choose, fixed costs show up sooner than expected. That makes the problem awkward for side projects. Building it yourself feels tedious, but paying for an external SaaS every time also feels wasteful. Eventually I ended up asking a simple question: Do I really have to solve this problem with a paid service every single time? That was when OCI Object Storage and Cloudflare R2 became interesting options. Both provide meaningful free tier capacity, and at side project scale they felt realistic enough to build around. So instead of choosing a fully managed service like Cloudinary, I decided to move toward a setup where…",
