      "locale": "en",
      "slug": "leemage-case-study",
      "title": "How Leemage Grew from a Cost Problem into a File Management Platform",
      "url": "/en/blog/leemage-case-study#it-started-as-an-upload-feature-but-turned-into-an-operations-problem",
      "excerpt": "The original goal was straightforward: reduce upload costs while keeping the developer experience practical enough to use in a real project. Once I started building it, I realized the real problem was not simply storing…",
      "content": "It Started as an Upload Feature, but Turned into an Operations Problem\nThe original goal was straightforward: reduce upload costs while keeping the developer experience practical enough to use in a real project. Once I started building it, I realized the real problem was not simply storing files. The more painful part was everything that came after storage: management, repeated reuse, and keeping things organized across projects. As more projects accumulate, the important question becomes less about \"Can I upload this file?\" and more about \"Where is it stored, what variants exist, and can I reuse it later?\" That is why Leemage did not stop at a single upload endpoint. I made files separable by project, used presigned URL uploads to keep the API server lightweight, and added an explicit confirm step so image transformation and variant management could happen after the upload completed. In other words, the architecture spent more time thinking about what happens after storage than before it.",
      "sectionTitle": "It Started as an Upload Feature, but Turned into an Operations Problem",
