      "title": "How Leemage Grew from a Cost Problem into a File Management Platform",
      "url": "/en/blog/leemage-case-study#leemage-architecture",
      "excerpt": "The overall flow is fairly simple. 1. The client first requests a presigned upload URL. 2. The API creates a pending file record and returns the presigned URL. 3. The client uploads the file directly to object storage.…",
      "content": "Leemage Architecture\nThe overall flow is fairly simple. 1. The client first requests a presigned upload URL. 2. The API creates a pending file record and returns the presigned URL. 3. The client uploads the file directly to object storage. 4. During the confirm step, Leemage validates the uploaded object and collects metadata. 5. If the file is an image, Sharp generates optimized variants such as WebP and stores them back in object storage. 6. Finally, the database stores the file metadata and variant references so other projects can consume them through the API or SDK. What mattered to me here was not the upload itself, but the separation of concerns in the flow. I did not want a heavy upload server, and I did not want storage to be tightly coupled to one provider. If you want to balance cost, performance, and operational convenience, it helps to think of the upload path, storage path, and delivery path as separate layers. Another design choice I cared about was treating OpenAPI as a single source of truth instead of just a documentation artifact. In Leemage, the web API docs UI, the YAML exposed at /api/v1/openapi, and the SDK synchronization flow are all connected around the sa…",
