      "id": "en/leemage-case-study/i-started-with-cost-but-ended-up-caring-about-performance-too",
      "locale": "en",
      "slug": "leemage-case-study",
      "title": "How Leemage Grew from a Cost Problem into a File Management Platform",
      "url": "/en/blog/leemage-case-study#i-started-with-cost-but-ended-up-caring-about-performance-too",
      "excerpt": "One of the more interesting parts of building Leemage was how quickly cost concerns turned into performance concerns as well. Image conversion is the clearest example. Instead of storing and serving a heavy PNG as is, c…",
      "content": "I Started with Cost, but Ended Up Caring about Performance Too\nOne of the more interesting parts of building Leemage was how quickly cost concerns turned into performance concerns as well. Image conversion is the clearest example. Instead of storing and serving a heavy PNG as is, converting it to WebP reduces both storage usage and transfer size. That is not just about making an image lighter. It directly affects storage cost, bandwidth cost, and the speed users experience. 10GB Cost Comparison If you imagine storing around 10GB of files, the difference between a typical paid storage setup and a free tier centered structure becomes obvious. That gap was the original motivation behind Leemage. In side projects, even when traffic is not huge, repeated uploads and a growing image library start creating cost pressure sooner than expected. I wanted a structure where that cost could be managed instead of merely accepted. PNG vs WebP Reduction The size reduction from converting PNG to WebP was also meaningful in practice. The Google WebP documentation explains that lossless WebP images can be about 26% smaller than PNG. The exact number will always depend on the image itself and the enco…",
