      "id": "en/leemage-case-study/the-moment-it-started-feeling-like-a-reusable-foundation",
      "locale": "en",
      "slug": "leemage-case-study",
      "title": "How Leemage Grew from a Cost Problem into a File Management Platform",
      "url": "/en/blog/leemage-case-study#the-moment-it-started-feeling-like-a-reusable-foundation",
      "excerpt": "Leemage started to feel less like an internal tool and more like an actual product once I reused it in other projects. Reusing a previously built upload flow makes a bigger difference than it sounds. It means a new proj…",
      "content": "The Moment It Started Feeling Like a Reusable Foundation\nLeemage started to feel less like an internal tool and more like an actual product once I reused it in other projects. Reusing a previously built upload flow makes a bigger difference than it sounds. It means a new project does not have to redesign uploads from scratch, and it can start with storage paths, URL rules, file lifecycle management, and deletion behavior already defined. In practice, I also used Leemage as a storage adapter in another side project called leesfield. That experience changed how I saw the project. Before that, it was closer to \"a tool I made because I was personally annoyed.\" After that, it started feeling more like infrastructure that reduces repeated work. The same upload feature becomes much more valuable when it shortens the startup cost of the next project. The moment you open an API to outside consumers, documentation quality starts to resemble product quality. That is why I did not want OpenAPI to be treated as a separate documentation chore. Keeping the spec, the web docs, and the SDK sync flow aligned was one of the most important decisions in Leemage.",
