      "excerpt": "Looking back, the most important part of Leemage was not a flashy technical choice. It was the decision to recognize file handling as a repeated problem and to avoid solving it in a one off way. Even in side projects, I…",
      "content": "Closing Thoughts\nLooking back, the most important part of Leemage was not a flashy technical choice. It was the decision to recognize file handling as a repeated problem and to avoid solving it in a one off way. Even in side projects, I try to focus less on whether I can implement a feature quickly and more on whether that feature represents a recurring problem. If it does, I want to leave behind something reusable. Leemage is probably the clearest example of that tendency in my work. It started from cost pressure, but it eventually became a project about operability, extensibility, and reuse.",
