      "excerpt": "When people talk about building software with AI agents, the phrase harness engineering comes up more and more often. At first it sounded a little grandiose to me. But after repeatedly working with AI coding assistants,…",
      "content": "Productivity in the AI Era Depends More on Structure than Code\nWhen people talk about building software with AI agents, the phrase harness engineering comes up more and more often. At first it sounded a little grandiose to me. But after repeatedly working with AI coding assistants, it started to feel like a very precise description. Productivity is no longer explained only by how well a model can generate code. What matters just as much is the environment the model works inside. If the documentation structure, working rules, current stage, and next action are unclear, the model becomes unstable very quickly. In practice, AI performance depends not only on the model itself, but also on the quality of the harness around it. AI Harness Structure I think this connects naturally to spec driven development as well. Spec driven development assumes that problems are defined before implementation, decisions are recorded, and work status is made explicit. That approach is useful in human collaboration too, but it becomes even more important with AI. Humans can often fill in blanks on their own. AI works much more reliably when the context is explicit and structured. lee spec kit started fro…",
