      "id": "en/why-i-built-lee-spec-kit/the-bigger-cost-was-not-code-generation-but-context-transfer",
      "locale": "en",
      "slug": "why-i-built-lee-spec-kit",
      "title": "Productivity in the AI Era Depends More on Structure than Code: Why I Built lee-spec-kit",
      "url": "/en/blog/why-i-built-lee-spec-kit#the-bigger-cost-was-not-code-generation-but-context-transfer",
      "excerpt": "When you actually build with AI coding assistants, the biggest cost often is not code generation itself. More often, the recurring cost is context transfer. This was not a problem I discovered only after I started worki…",
      "content": "The Bigger Cost Was Not Code Generation, but Context Transfer\nWhen you actually build with AI coding assistants, the biggest cost often is not code generation itself. More often, the recurring cost is context transfer. This was not a problem I discovered only after I started working with AI. I had seen the same pattern many times while working at a company. The code was there, but the intent behind it was often missing. You could see the final result, but not the planning context or the decision making process that led to it. In practice, a new developer often needed help from someone who already knew the background in order to truly understand the codebase. Every project has different docs, different rules, and different ways of expressing progress. When that happens, you end up repeating the same explanations to AI over and over again. Where was this feature discussed? What decisions led here? Are we in the spec stage or the plan stage? What still needs to be checked before a PR? If that information is not organized consistently, humans get confused and AI gets unstable. Under those conditions, even a very good model struggles to produce stable output. Every new repository effec…",
