      "slug": "why-i-built-lee-spec-kit",
      "title": "Productivity in the AI Era Depends More on Structure than Code: Why I Built lee-spec-kit",
      "url": "/en/blog/why-i-built-lee-spec-kit#but-i-did-not-want-to-copy-the-existing-structure-as-is",
      "excerpt": "At the same time, I did not want to adopt that structure unchanged. What I wanted was not to transplant a methodology directly, but to build a CLI that could be applied more lightly and more quickly to the way I actuall…",
      "content": "But I Did Not Want to Copy the Existing Structure as-is\nAt the same time, I did not want to adopt that structure unchanged. What I wanted was not to transplant a methodology directly, but to build a CLI that could be applied more lightly and more quickly to the way I actually work. The feature level flow needed to stay clear, and the documentation structure needed to be lightweight without becoming vague for AI. At this point, a natural question follows: \"Why not just use an existing tool?\" Someone could reasonably think of options like oh my opencode. I think that question is valid. But the problem I wanted to solve was closer to designing a harness for my own working context than simply adopting another general purpose AI development tool. In other words, I did not want to remain only a user who knows how to use good tools. I wanted to work directly on the question of how to structure my own work system. lee spec kit is the result of that choice. Tailored Workflow System",
