      "id": "en/surviving-one-year-as-an-ordinary-developer/developer-language-was-not-enough",
      "locale": "en",
      "slug": "surviving-one-year-as-an-ordinary-developer",
      "title": "Surviving One Year as an Ordinary Developer",
      "url": "/en/blog/surviving-one-year-as-an-ordinary-developer#developer-language-was-not-enough",
      "excerpt": "Another thing I learned very quickly was that it is not enough to speak only in terms developers understand. At school, most of my teammates were developers, and we usually shared a technical context already. At work, t…",
      "content": "Developer Language Was Not Enough\nAnother thing I learned very quickly was that it is not enough to speak only in terms developers understand. At school, most of my teammates were developers, and we usually shared a technical context already. At work, that was not the case. I had to discuss the same problems with planners, QA, and other people who were not writing the code themselves. I had to explain what I understood in a way they could understand too, and I had to describe why a change was necessary and how the behavior would change in language that non developers could also follow. Looking back, that mattered almost as much as technical growth. Development was not something that ended with my own understanding. It was also the work of helping other people see the same problem from the same direction.",
      "sectionTitle": "Developer Language Was Not Enough",
